## Executive Summary
In this lab, I analyze the credit card RFID skimming attack demonstrated by Pablos Holman in 
his TEDxMidwest talk. The attack exploited a fundamental design flaw in the early release of
RFID-enabled credit cards, also known as "contactless", that transmit unencrypted data to any
nearby reader, allowing an attacker to capture sensitive data in a plaintext format, such 
as the cardholder's name, card number, and expiration date. By using equipment under $50, an 
attacker could silently intercept the data from the victim without making any physical contact. 
While Modern contactless cards have addressed this issue by implementing advanced encryption  
and tokenization, this attack remains a clear example of how convenience features can introduce 
security vulnerabilities that affect millions of people, before the affected cards could be 
recalled or replaced.

---

## Technical Analysis
### The Vulnerability
Radio Frequency Identification (RFID) is a technology that uses radio waves to wirelessly
transfer data and identify objects at short range. AN RFID credit card consists of three 
components: an RFID chip that electronically stores the cardholder's information, an antenna
responsible for receiving radio signals, and the card body itself, which houses both components.

In a transaction, a payment terminal initiates the exchange by emitting a radio signal that
activates the chip in the card. The chip responds by transmitting the cardholder's information
back to the terminal for the transaction to be completed. In the early stages of RFID, the
cardholder's information was broadcast to the terminal in plaintext without an authentication 
mechanism to verify the identity of the receiving device. Therefore, anyone with a reader, 
legitimate or not, would receive the same information.

### How the Attack Works
The attack required minimal equipment, only a commercially available RFID reader, which at 
the time cost under $50. With the reader, an attacker would have to place themselves within 
a few centimeters away from their victim, usually in a crowded area where they would raise no
suspicion. As the reader transmits radio signals to activate the chip, the attacker starts 
receiving without any authorization, all the cardholder's information - name, card number, 
and  expiration date - in plaintext.

The entire interaction would only last milliseconds and required no physical contact with
the victim. The victim had no way of knowing the information was transmitted, and the stolen
data could be cloned onto a blank RFID card to be used for fraudulent purchases anywhere or
even be sold on dark web marketplaces, further extending the attacker's profit.

---

## Impact Assessment
At the individual level, a victim of RFID skimming will not only face a single fraudulent charge,
but the unauthorized charges may go unnoticed for weeks, accumulating financial damage and 
triggering lengthy processes with card issuers. In the case of cloned cards being sold on the
dark web marketplace, victims may face repeated fraud charges over extended periods.

The severity of this vulnerability has major consequences since the issue is embedded in the
hardware that has been distributed to millions of people. Unlike a software vulnerability, which
could be patched, in this case, all the distributed cards will have to be recalled or replaced
with new ones. This is a prime example of why developing and implementing security should be 
considered in the development of hardware and software.


